The Plant does not require its employees to participate in conducting offensive-type emergency response activities under the HAZWOPER standard; a "Non-responding Facility Policy" has been adopted for the Plant as a whole.  In the event of an ammonia emergency, the response is to follow the procedures in the Equipment SOP's and the California Hazardous Material Business Plan.  The overall procedure is to shutdown if it can be done safely by qualified personnel, evacuate, and notify the local response agencies and WPS (technical support).  Plant employees are to implement hazard communications, provide for the safety of visitors and report to the established Evacuation Staging Area(s) for a head count.  Emergency response is coordinated with the City of Monterey County Health Department/CUPA and local Fire Department.  Coastal Cooling has verified it is included in the Monterey County Area Emergency Plan. 



6.    Planned changes to improve safety



The primary mechanisms to identify and plan safety improvements include (but are not limited to):

-  Process Hazard Analysis review;

-  Compliance Audits;

-  Routine inspections, tests & maintenance (Mechanical Integrity Program);

-  IIAR Bulletin 109 Inspections (IIAR Minimum Safety Criteria For The Safe Operation Of Ammonia Refrigeration Process);

-  Coastal Cooling and WPS Internal Inspection Protocols

-  Incident Investigation



The Programs above may result in recommendations ranging from capital improvements to routine maintenance of the plant.  Service calls are established in parallel to identified needs.  



